l,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"## Description\r\nI noticed that the CMake command `find_package(PythonInterp)` is run before checking whether we need to build the self-tests, which on my computer ends up with the following warning since there is no Python interpreter configured (when using Catch2 as a sub-project):\r\n\r\n> -- Could NOT find PythonInterp (missing: PYTHON_EXECUTABLE)\r\n\r\nSince I was drowning into other errors I wondered at the time whether this warning affected my issues, then I realized that it only mattered when building the self-tests and not when using Catch2 as a CMake sub-project.\r\n\r\nCouldn't the `find_package` be nested into the following condition so that the warning only occurs when trying to build the self-tests?\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\nI use [DownloadProject](https://github.com/Crascit/DownloadProject) from my testsuite's CMakeLists.txt to fetch the latest version of Catch2, then I call `add_subdirectory` on the resulting directory before declaring `Catch2::Catch2` as library used by my testsuite.\r\n\r\nConsidering the CMakeLists.txt in the main Catch2 repository, it should happen whenever Catch2 is used as a CMake sub-project anyway.\r\n\r\n### Extra information\r\n* Catch version: **v2.3.0**\r\n","closed_by":{"login":"horenmar","id":9026413,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjkwMjY0MTM=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/9026413?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/horenmar","html_url":"https://github.com/horenmar","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/horenmar/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/horenmar/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/horenmar/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/horenmar/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ho